Instead of implicitly differentiating, we first solve the equation for
\emph{q} and then differentiate normally.

\begin{align*}
q^2+p^{3/2}+2p &=20 \\
q^2 &=20-p^{3/2}-2p \\
q &=\sqrt{20-p^{3/2}-2p}\end{align*}

Then

\begin{align*}\frac{dq}{dp} = \frac{-(3/2)p^{1/2}-2}{2\sqrt{20-p^{3/2}-2p}}\end{align*}

Substituting in $p = 4$ gives

\begin{align*}\frac{dq}{dp} = \frac{-(3/2)(4)^{1/2}-2}{2\sqrt{20-(4)^{3/2}-2(4)}} = \frac{-(3/2)(2)-2}{2\sqrt{20-8-8}} = \frac{-5}{4}\end{align*}
